Adding on to Jon&#39;s answer, I agree, the map is the sole property of the current thread.

    ThreadLocalMap getMap(Thread t) {
        return t.threadLocals;
    }


And this ThreadLocalMap stores a table inside which only refers to the calling ThreadLocal object (which sits in the Heap space, i.e. common to all threads) for getting hash index into the table. But the actual value is stored inside this table which is per thread.

So if your ThreadLocal object is shared between multiple threads and each thread call get or set at the same time on it, they&#39;re literally setting the values in their own copies of the table contained inside ThreadLocalMap which is stored inside Thread class as a non static field.

